\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Three forms of fusion shown as coefficient-vector and coefficient-matrix schematics. Rows labeled $x_1$ and $x_2$ denote predictors. In Panel B, columns $y_1$ and $y_2$ denote related responses or tasks. In Panel C, columns $g_1$ and $g_2$ denote groups of observations. Colored links indicate which objects are coupled by the fusion penalty. Panel A shows fused lasso penalties on ordered coefficients \citep  {tibshirani2005fused}. Panel B shows graph-guided multi-task fusion across related responses or tasks \citep  {chen2010graph,chen2012smoothing}. Panel C shows grouped fused regression, where the fusion graph is placed on groups of observations \citep  {dondelinger2020joint}.}}{4}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:fusion-matrix-concepts}{{1}{4}{Three forms of fusion shown as coefficient-vector and coefficient-matrix schematics. Rows labeled $x_1$ and $x_2$ denote predictors. In Panel B, columns $y_1$ and $y_2$ denote related responses or tasks. In Panel C, columns $g_1$ and $g_2$ denote groups of observations. Colored links indicate which objects are coupled by the fusion penalty. Panel A shows fused lasso penalties on ordered coefficients \citep {tibshirani2005fused}. Panel B shows graph-guided multi-task fusion across related responses or tasks \citep {chen2010graph,chen2012smoothing}. Panel C shows grouped fused regression, where the fusion graph is placed on groups of observations \citep {dondelinger2020joint}}{figure.1}{}}
